{"Response":{"Module":{"ModuleCode":"CLAS0123","ModuleIdentifier":"4FE36DF873F411E89A86FAE8722E8321","ModuleTitle":"Classical Athens in Modern Political Theory","ModuleContact":{"Faculty":{"FacultyCode":"ART","FacultyName":"Faculty of Arts and Humanities"},"Department":{"DepartmentCode":"GRKLT_ART","DepartmentName":"Greek and Latin"}},"ModuleValue":"20","ModuleStudyHours":"200","ModuleLearningHours":"20","ModuleSearchKeywords":"GREEK LITERATURE, GREEK CULTURE, PHILOSOPHY","Email":"classics.office@ucl.ac.uk","ModuleSuperGroup":"Classical Athens in Modern Political Theory","CEFRLevel":"","ModuleInstance":{"AcademicYearCode":"2019","AcademicYearDescription":"2019/20 academic  year","ModuleInstanceDescription":"<p class=\"p\" helvetica=\"\" lucida=\"\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.5em; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; font-size: 16px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: \">\n\t<span style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px; font-weight: 600;\">Content:&nbsp;</span>This MA module explores the reception of classical Athens within modern political theory. It investigates the continuing legacy of ancient political thought in modern theorisations of the political from the late eighteenth century to the present day. Why did classical texts and ancient political institutions continue to exert such a powerful influence on the diverse traditions of modern political philosophy? How does the understanding of ancient politics change at the time of the American and French Revolutions? What do different representations of Athens tell us about the evolving conceptualization of democracy? How do questions of gender, class, race and slavery impact on modern engagements with the Greek polis? The module will consider a series of key texts including extracts from works by Plato, Aristotle, Hegel, Marx, Nietzsche, Arendt, Foucault, Bonnie Honig, Judith Butler and Ranci&egrave;re.&nbsp;</p>\n<p class=\"p\" helvetica=\"\" lucida=\"\" style=\"margin: 0px 0px 1.5em; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; font-size: 16px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: \">\n\t<strong>Skills:&nbsp;</strong><span style=\"color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-size: 12px;\">This module will enable participants to gain a deeper understanding of the reception of concepts developed in Classical Athens in the modern world and to develop techniques to interpret relevant texts and to discuss them orally and in writing.</span></p>\n<p class=\"p\" helvetica=\"\" lucida=\"\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; font-size: 16px; vertical-align: baseline; background-image: initial; background-position: 0px 0px; background-size: initial; background-repeat: initial; background-attachment: initial; background-origin: initial; background-clip: initial; color: rgb(51, 51, 51); font-family: \">\n\t<span style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; outline: 0px; vertical-align: baseline; background: 0px 0px; font-weight: 600;\">Recommended preperatory reading:</span>&nbsp;All texts will be read in translation.</p>\n","ModuleInstanceRestriction":"","ModuleInstanceSubjectCollection":{"ModuleInstanceSubject":["Philosophy","Classics"]},"ModuleDeliveryCollection":{"ModuleDelivery":[{"ModuleDeliveryIdentifier":"5006D36A73F411E89A86FAE8722E8321","LevelOfStudy":"Postgraduate","ModuleDeliveryPeriod":{"PeriodCode":"T2","PeriodTitle":"Term 2"},"AcademicLevel":{"AcademicLevelCode":"L7","AcademicLevelTitle":"FHEQ Level 7"},"ModuleDeliveryType":"","ModeOfStudy":"Face-to-fa